So after looking into this some more, I've learned that arrays are always passed by reference, but that only 
means you can change attributes and individual items in an array. So for example:

var a = [1, 2, 3, 4];
var f = function(x){x = null;};
f(a);
// the value of a will remain [1, 2, 3, 4]
// but if instead:
var g = function(x){x[0] = null;};
g(a);
// the value of a is now [null, 2, 3, 4]

In the attached example, the Google Closure compiled version is akin to the function f above, which means 
that the value of the arrays should *not* be changing. In IE, if the threshold is set high enough, however, they 
do indeed change. So the original report may not be accurate, but this is a real issue.

There is definitely something odd occurring here, running it under the debugger with 
IE7, it reports "Number expected".

Adding a "Debug.writeln("blah")" in the "right" spot and the problem goes away:
    var g_test=function(f,c){
        var g=["aaaaaa","bbbbbb"];
        c=(function(a,b){
          for(var d=[],e=0;e<a;e+=1)
            d.push(b);
          return d})(c,g);
        c.sort(function(a,b){
          a=(a[1].toUpperCase());
          Debug.writeln("Blah");
          b=(b[1].toUpperCase());
          return a<b?-1:Number(a>b)});
        f.innerHTML=typeof c[0]+"<br>"+c.join(" --- ")
     };

If you don't want to wait for the compiler fix, just declare the variables outside of 
the sort, and the compiler won't optimize and reuse them:

var a, b;
c.sort(function(a1,b1){
          a=(a1[1].toUpperCase());
          Debug.writeln("Blah");
          b=(b1[1].toUpperCase());
          return a<b?-1:Number(a>b)});

wow. that's a nice find. i can't imagine what IE could possibly be doing under the 
covers that would lead to this problem.

One possible fix would be to never coalesce the arguments of a function. 

Another possible fix would be to "fix" Array.prototype.sort:

var oldArraySort = Array.prototype.sort;
Array.prototype.sort = function(f) {
  return oldArraySort.call(this, function(x, y) {
    return f.call(this, x, y);
  });
};

Neither is really satisfying.

Alan, what do you think?
